## 🚨 Problem 3: Parallel CSS System (Breaks Your Architecture)

Your established architecture uses:
- **CSS Modules** (`.module.css`) for component-scoped styles
- **Design tokens** via CSS custom properties in `shared.css` (e.g., `--color-primary`, `--space-sm`)
- **Utility classes** like `.btn-primary`, `.card`, `.input-field` that reference tokens

Santiago's branch adds **219 lines** of new global CSS classes to `shared.css` with a completely different naming convention:

```css
/* His additions — NOT using CSS Modules, NOT following your naming */
.learning-page { ... }
.learning-header { ... }
.learning-card { ... }
.learning-section-title { ... }
.learning-muted { ... }
.learning-button { ... }
.learning-button-secondary { ... }
.learning-pill { ... }
.learning-empty { ... }
.learning-grid-2 { ... }
.learning-stat-grid-5 { ... }
```

Then in JSX files, he replaces your established patterns:

```diff
- className="rounded-lg bg-blue-500 px-4 py-2 text-sm font-semibold text-white shadow"
+ className="learning-button disabled:cursor-not-allowed disabled:opacity-60"
```

> [!WARNING]
> This creates a **second parallel design system** alongside yours. It mixes global utility classes with Tailwind utilities (like `disabled:cursor-not-allowed`), completely bypassing CSS Modules. This will cause namespace collisions and makes styles harder to trace and maintain.

